Megaline's commercial department wants to know which plan brings in more revenue, Surf or Ultimate, so they can adjust their advertising budget.¶

Tasks:

  • Carry out preliminary analysis using data from 500 Megaline clients
    • Convert data to necessary types
    • Find and eliminate errors in the data
    • Provide an explanation of errors found and how they were eliminated/processed
  • Evaluate:
    • Who the clients are
    • Where are the clients from
    • Which plan the clients use
    • The number of calls made in 2018
    • The number of texts sent in 2018
  • Analyze clients behavior
    • For each client, find:
      • The number of calls made each month
      • The number of minutes used each month
      • The number of texts sent each month
      • The volume of data used each month
      • The monthly revenue
  • Determine which prepaid plan brings in more revenue
    • Test the following hypotheses:
      • The average revenue from users of Ultimate and Surf calling plans differs
      • The average revenue from users in NYNJ area is different from that of the users from other regions.
    • Explain
      • The formulation of the null and althernative hypotheses
      • What criterion you used to test the hypotheses and why.

Important notes:

  • Megaline rounds seconds to minutes for each call (1 second rounds to 1 minute)
  • Megaline rounds mbs to gbs for the whole month, there are 1024mb in 1gb (1025mb rounds to 2gb)

  • churn_date column: the date the user stopped using the service (if the value is missing, the calling plan was being used when this data was generated)

  • Plan details:

    • Surf
      • Monthly charge: 20 dollars
      • 500 monthly minutes, 50 texts, and 15 GB of data
      • After exceeding the package limits:
        • 1 minute: 3 cents
        • 1 text message: 3 cents
        • 1 GB of data: 10 dollars
    • Ultimate
      • Monthly charge: 70 dollars
      • 3000 monthly minutes, 1000 text messages, and 30 GB of data
      • After exceeding the package limits:
        • 1 minute: 1 cent
        • 1 text message: 1 cent
        • 1 GB of data: 7 dollars

Plan of action¶

  1. Import Libraries
  2. Open the data files and study the general information
  3. Data Preprocessing
    • 3.a. Clean up the data
    • 3.b. Calculate requested information
  4. Analyze the data
  5. Answer hypotheses questions

  • All files except megaline_plans.csv has a 'user_id' column which is a unique user identifier
  • There are 500 unique clients in this sample data - confirmed by the megaline_users.csv file
  • The megaline_calls.csv, megaline_internet.csv, and megaline_messages.csv files have 481, 489, and 402 unique users, respectively, represented in their respective files
    • not all users used all forms of communication, i.e. made calls, sent messages, or used the internet
  • The megaline_calls.csv, megaline_internet.csv, and megaline_messages.csv files all contain an 'id' column
    • This could become confusing later, so the column name should be change to represent the file it is from
  • Most calls, internet usage, and messages happened in the second half of December

File based information

    • duration: duration of the call (in minutes)

Internet file:

  • 104825 entries

  • contains:

Messages file:

  • contains:

3.a. Conclusion of Data Preprocessing¶

Actions Performed and Information gathered

  • Working dataframes of each file were created
  • 'id' columns were renamed in megaline_calls.csv, megaline_internet.csv, and megaline_messages.csv files to represent the file it comes from
  • Missing values were found in one dataframe: users
    • churn_date column in users data has 466 missing values
    • This accounts for 93.2% of the users
    • According to the instructions given, churn_date = the date the user stopped using the service (if the value is missing, the calling plan was being used when this data was generated)
      • so 466 or 93.2% users were active during the collection time of the data
    • Removing this information would signiticantly impact the results
    • The missing values were changed to None
      • It would be inappropriate to fill this data with an average or median
  • No duplicates were found in all five dataframes
  • object data types were changed to datetime data types in the following dataframes where appropriate:
    • calls (call_date)
    • interenet (session_date)
    • messages (message_date)
    • users (reg_date, churn_date)
  • Calls lasting for 0 minutes were examined
    • 478 out of 481 clients that made calls had at least one 0 minute call
      • This accounts for 99.5% of the users who made calls
    • Zero minute calls make up 19.5% of the data provided
    • These could be missed, dropped, or cancelled calls
    • Going forward with analysis:
      • Number of minutes used is not affected if I remove or keep the 0 minute calls
      • Number of calls is affected if I remove or keep the 0 minute calls
      • I am leaving them because they are still calls even if they didnt use any minutes and I think they should be accounted for
  • Sessions lasting for 0 mbs were examined
    • 477 out of 489 clients that used data had at least one 0 mb session
      • This accounts for 99.5% of users who used data
    • Zero mb sessions make up 13.1% of the data provided
    • These could be clients who lost internet or service, used wi-fi, or opened a browser but didnt go to a website
    • Going forward with analysis:
      • The volume of data used is not affected if I remove or keep the 0 mb sessions
      • The number of sessions is affected if I remove or keep the 0 mb sessions
      • I am leaving them because removing further analysis does not call for the number of sessions but the volume of data used, so this will not affect those calculations
Reviewer's comment Thank you for such deteiled conclusion! Your decisions about 0 minutes and 0 mbs are absolutely right! Perfect!

3.b. Calculate the following information¶

For each client, find:

  • The number of calls made each month
  • The number of minutes used each month
  • The number of texts sent each month
  • The volume of data used each month
  • The monthly revenue
    • subtract the free package limit from the total number of calls, text messages, and data
    • multiply the result by the calling plan value
    • add the monthly charge depending on the calling plan

Plan of action:

  • Create a new column with month number in each dataframe
  • Use pivot tables to find:
    • The number of calls made each month
    • The number of minutes used each month - rounded up
    • The number of texts sent each month
    • The volume of data used each month - rounded up
  • Join the tables together for easier analysis
  • Calculate the monthly revenue
    • monthly minutes charge
    • monthly texts charge
    • monthly data charge
    • total monthly charge

# Create a function to calculate the charge for minutes used each month
def mins_charge(row, month_num):
    month_mins = 'mins_{}'.format(month_num)
    if row['reg_date'].month <= month_num:
        extra_mins_act = (row[month_mins] - row['minutes_included']) * row['usd_per_minute']
        if extra_mins_act >= 0:
            return extra_mins_act
        else:
            return 0
    else:
        return 0
    
for month in months.keys():
    month_value = '{}_mins_charge'.format(month)
    user_usage_data[month_value] = user_usage_data.apply(mins_charge, args=(months[month],), axis=1) # args requires a tuple

# Create a function that calculates the total monthly charge for each client
# Need to account for active and inactive months
import numpy as np
def monthly_total(row, month_name, month_num):
    mins_monthly_charge = '{}_mins_charge'.format(month_name)
    texts_monthly_charge = '{}_texts_charge'.format(month_name)
    gbs_monthly_charge = '{}_gbs_charge'.format(month_name)
    if row['reg_date'].month <= month_num and 'NaT' in str(row['churn_date']):
        monthly_total_act = row['usd_monthly_pay'] + row[mins_monthly_charge] + row[texts_monthly_charge] + row[gbs_monthly_charge]
        return monthly_total_act
    elif row['reg_date'].month <= month_num and row['churn_date'].month >= month_num:
        total_monthly_charge_inact = row['usd_monthly_pay'] + row[mins_monthly_charge] + row[texts_monthly_charge] + row[gbs_monthly_charge]
        return total_monthly_charge_inact
    else:
        return 0

for month in months.keys():
    total_monthly_charge = '{}_total'.format(month)
    user_usage_data[total_monthly_charge] = user_usage_data.apply(monthly_total, args=(month, months[month]), axis=1)

5 Test the hypothesis questions¶

Info on testing hypothesis

A test of a statistical hypothesis always begins with a statement of the hypothesis. First, we state the null hypothesis, H₀. For example, "The mean of the population in question equals A," where A is some number. The alternative hypothesis, H₁, is based on H₀. For this H₀, H₁ would be, "The mean of the population does not equal A." H₀ is always stated with an equal sign.

We construct a distribution based on the assumption that H₀ is true. In this case, it would be a normal distribution around the parameter of interest, the mean. The variance or its square root, the standard deviation (a measure of the distribution's dispersion, or scatter), is estimated based on the sample.

Hypothesis on the Equality of the Means of Two Populations

Sometimes you need to compare the means of two different statistical populations. In order to test your hypothesis that the means of two statistical populations are equal based on samples taken from them, apply the method scipy.stats.ttest_ind(). The method takes the following parameters:

  • array1, array2 are arrays containing the samples.
  • equal_var is an optional parameter that specifies whether or not the variances of the populations should be considered equal.

If there is reason to believe that the samples were taken from populations with similar parameters, then set equal_var = True, and the variance of each sample will be estimated from the combined dataset from the two samples, not separately from the values in each sample. This gives us more accurate results. However, we only do this if the variances of the statistical populations from which the samples are taken are approximately equal. Otherwise, we need to set equal_var = False; by default, it's Hypothesis on the Equality of the Means of Paired Samples equal_var = True.

Plan of Action

  • Obtain needed information to perform tests
    • tables
    • queries
  • Evaluate dispersion of data sets
    • if the dispersion is similar then the parameter equal_var=True
    • if the dispersion is not similar then the parameter equal_var=False

# Test a hypothesis about the means of two statistical populations based on samples taken from them

surf_monthly_totals_list = [3502.93, 11759.43, 21693.88, 1328.34, 600, 9209.41, 6426.71, 2393.23, 5077.49, 16520.3, 16213.15, 12462.75]
ultimate_monthly_totals_list = [3703., 8253., 11347., 2170., 1330., 7042., 6167., 2926., 4571., 10577.,  9625.,  8925.]

alpha = 0.05 # 5% as the critical statistical significance level

results = st.ttest_ind(
    surf_monthly_totals_list, 
    ultimate_monthly_totals_list,
        equal_var = False)

print('p-value: ', results.pvalue)

if results.pvalue < alpha: # your code: compare the p-value you get with the significance level):
    print("We reject the null hypothesis that the average revenue from users of Ultimate and Surf calling plans differs.") 
    print("The alternative hypthosesis is true: The average revenue from users of Ultimate and Surf calling plans do not differ.")
else:
    print("We can't reject the null hypothesis that the average revenue from users of Ultimate and Surf calling plans differs.")
    print("The null hypothesis is true: The average revenue from users of Ultimate and Surf calling plans differs.")

The null hypothesis is true: The average revenue from users of Ultimate and Surf calling plans differs.
